metadata.name: FxPlanet #214
metadata.description:
üü¢„Ä∞Storyline„Ä∞üü¢

Once upon a time, a God had a little daughter. The daughter liked to explore the planets on his father's cosmos. Suddenly the daughter got sick and died like a collapsing star. God gets alone, angry, depressed and finally mad. He turned all the universe to ash and mixed the ash of her daughter's soul with it to make her alive, But he failed. In the end, he decided to destroy himself to make a New cosmos of all generative planets from ash of himself and his daughter's soul to one more time in the eternity they can be with each other in a heart of a planet. If you listen carefully to the planets, you may hear them calling each other.

‚¨õ‚¨õ‚¨õ‚¨õ‚¨õ‚¨õ‚¨õ

üî¥„Ä∞Rarity„Ä∞üî¥

This collection is a 3D generative interactive artwork (Made with Unity Game Engine) that contains of 9999+1 planets (1 shared source of light and 9999 pieces of souls) from billions of variation. You can see more random variations from fxhash page.
‚óº The beauty and complexity of the Planet's surface is important, But what is going on inside?
Each planet has three grades of volume (High, Medium, Low) that show you what resources exist on the planets (Common, Rare, Legendary).
Some resources are so valuable and infrequent.
‚óº For Example: It's possible to get Oxygen (Legendary Resource) on Low volume slot, but it's infrequent if you get it on High volume slot.
‚óº Checkout Material rarity list on webpage.

metadata.name: Rebug #516
metadata.description:
A debug view of the underlying particulate algorithm of Atoms' Gaze and Quantum Folly. Refined as a gift for collectors.

Enjoy watching the structures form. Once it's fully rendered you can download a full resolution image of 3508 x 4961 px by ***double clicking/tapping***. At this size the piece is printable at A3 size at 300 dpi. If you're interested in acquiring a signed print please contact @KRANKARTA.

Created on Chrome desktop 103.0 on 2022-08-06 in javascript and GLSL. Results on other browsers/devices may vary.

metadata.name: Human #16
metadata.description:
Who are you? 

Are you the person you were yesterday?

Or did you change today? 

What is this "I" we are talking about? What determines our identity?

We walk on the ground and touch the soil. We smell, taste, hear and see. Are we something more?

metadata.name: BlockonBlock #182
metadata.description:
‚ÄòBlockonBlock‚Äô is the precursor and reserve pass for the upcoming ‚ÄòHashway ‚Äò69 Revisited‚Äô collection by pixelwank. 
Free mint for pixelwank holders on tezos - After 3 days any remainders will be opened up to the public for 2tez.  

‚ÄòBlockonBlock‚Äô was a study of rectangles following on from the use of circles in Generacci. 
Placements & building sizes are based on numbers from the fibonacci sequence. 

I had a blast making these and I hope they bring the collector as much enjoyment.

'Hashway '69 Revisited' coming soon :)

23 colour palettes 
14 colour overlays 
21% chance of extra lines
Click the image or press ‚Äòs‚Äô or ‚ÄòS‚Äô in live move to save a 3000x3000 png 

Thanks for collectin‚Äô & shoutouts to Circolors for the support <3 

R.I.F.F. 
Remember it‚Äôs for fun

metadata.name: Duet #88
metadata.description:
by Daeinc
Aug 2022

Duet explores generative+computational motion and creates an almost infinite sequence of visual compositions. Two groups of shapes transform, merge, and split randomly. What can be disorienting starts to make sense as every element is animated from one to the other. This transition animation is what connects random pieces and creates a relationship between them. Each element is mathematically interpolated, with its motion defined by an equation. 

Although there are key moments, it is hard to summarize time-based work as a static image. As a constantly evolving generative motion piece, Duet invites viewers to form their impression by feeling the rhythm over time.

## Guide:
- The animation responds to window aspect ratio. It reproduces the same outcome at the same ratio. 
- For reliable playback, keep the window active and use IPFS view.
- See browser console for more info.
- Tested on MacOS 12.5.1 with Chromium 104.0

## Keyboard Interaction
- [n] to play a new random loop.
- [spacebar] to play/pause.
- [s] to save PNG. use URL params for dimensions.
- [up] and [down] to change shape resolution.
- [left] and [right] to change BPM. only works while looping. 
- [h] to toggle high DPI mode. off by default.
- [p] to toggle pixel snapping. off by default.

## URL Parameters
- add parameters separated by ampersand to the URL ex. https://.../?fxhash=...&w=1200&h=600
- [w] and [h]: set width and height in pixels. (ex. w=1200&h=600)
- [s] and [e]: set starting and ending keyframes (inclusive) for loop. (ex. s=20&e=24) 
- setting large values for start/end is not advised.
- [len]: instead of start/end, set a loop length between 1 and 16. (ex. len=4)
- [bpm]: beats per minute. (ex. bpm=80)
- [res]: shape resolution between 0 and 18. (ex. res=2)
- [pr]: pixel ratio. set it to 2 (or press [h]) for hi-DPI screens.
- [ar]: maximum aspect ratio. set to any value over 1. 1.2 by default.
- [snap]: add the param to snap to pixel grid.

## License
CC BY-NC 4.0
Please refer to the included LICENSE.md for license information.
Libraries used: canvas-sketch, canvas-sketch-util, dom-events, hsv2rgb, keyframes, equations from easings.net, array shuffle from stackoverflow.

metadata.name: color combinations #158
metadata.description:
the 'color combinations' series was developed as an exercise of combining colors from a single defined palette and the attempt to make all 15 selected colors being able to work within each other.

the constant pursuit for perfectionism made me design more than 200 tentatives of creating a perfect circle, and therefore the circle is the rarest output for the series.

i hope this series serves as a reference and inspire everyone out there.

2,340 possible combinations.
the closer the shape to the circle the rarer - ranging from 100% to 5%.
the bigger the shape the rarer - ranging from 30% to 20%.
beige and black colors are rarer - ranging from 100% to 5%

metadata.name: Bloc.Plan #103
metadata.description:
Working as an architect and interior designer daily, I always find that creating space is something interesting. Especially a block plan. As an architectural drawing, it serves to inform the viewer of the presence or absence of a space by composing positive and negative spaces on the site. Through this, I found out that block plan can be a captivating visual art as well.

Press [s] to save captured image

created using p5.js
dirbots - Aug22

üü¢„Ä∞Storyline„Ä∞üü¢

Once upon a time, a God had a little daughter. The daughter liked to explore the planets on his father's cosmos. Suddenly the daughter got sick and died like a collapsing star. God gets alone, angry, depressed and finally mad. He turned all the universe to ash and mixed the ash of her daughter's soul with it to make her alive, But he failed. In the end, he decided to destroy himself to make a New cosmos of all generative planets from ash of himself and his daughter's soul to one more time in the eternity they can be with each other in a heart of a planet. If you listen carefully to the planets, you may hear them calling each other.

‚óº The beauty and complexity of the Planet's surface is important, But what is going on inside?
Each planet has three grades of volume (High, Medium, Low) that show you what resources exist on the planets (Common, Rare, Legendary).
Some resources are so valuable and infrequent.
‚óº For Example: It's possible to get Oxygen (Legendary Resource) on Low volume slot, but it's infrequent if you get it on High volume slot.
